result.execSummary:
The defendant Andrew Stephen Wojak-Hanson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Narcotic Drugs, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(am).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Court orders defendant to pay all cost, fees and surcharges, including DNA surcharge by 11/7/2016 or a civil judgment to be entered with tax intercept.  Bail on deposit to be applied if applicable.
Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.

Consecutive to: CONSECUTIVE to any sentence with credit for 62 days served; Straight time. Court recommends against electronic monitoring.   Huber privileges allowed only for the Milwaukee County Day Reporting Center.
Court does not suspend driving privileges.

Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor. Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.

Defendant Andrew Stephen Wojak-Hanson in court with attorney Caitlin Hazard Firer.  Defendant Andrew Stephen Wojak-Hanson in custody.  Brad A. Vorpahl appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Deputy court clerk: LMS.  

The parties have agreed to a Milwaukee County Drug Treatment Court deferred prosecution agreement and participation contract.
The defendant was advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, entered a plea of GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum to Plea Questionnaire received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea. Defendant further advised that if he/she is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  The Court found the defendant guilty but WITHHELD entry of Judgement of Conviction.  The court approved the Milwaukee County Drug Treatment Court Deferred Prosecution Agreement and Participant Contract and ordered the proceedings suspended for an initial period of 12 months to 18 months.  Court ordered case adjourned for review hearing in Branch 6.  FILE RETAINED IN COURT.  Review hearing scheduled for October 2, 2014 at 09:30 am.
